# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: maritime-silk-road
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The **21st Century Maritime Silk Road** (Chinese: 21世纪海上丝绸之路), commonly just **Maritime Silk Road** (**MSR**), is the sea route part of the Belt and Road Initiative which is a Chinese strategic initiative to increase investment and foster collaboration across the historic Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The China–Pakistan Economic Corridor is an extension of the proposed Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The Maritime Silk Road coincides with the theory of China's String of Pearls strategy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The Maritime Silk Road initiative was first proposed by Chinese leader Xi Jinping during a speech to the Indonesian Parliament in October 2013.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] In November 2014, Chinese leader Xi Jinping announced plans to create a USD $40 billion development fund, which would help finance China's plans to develop the New Silk Road and the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] China has accelerated its drive to draw Africa into the MSR with the speedy construction of a modern standard-gauge rail link between Nairobi and Mombasa.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] In March 2015, the National Development and Reform Commission of China publicly released a document titled *Vision and Actions on Jointly Building Silk Road Economic Belt and 21st-Century Maritime Silk Road*, which discusses the principles and framework which form the foundation of the initiative.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Although the routes encompassed in the MSR will be copious if the initiative comes to fruition, to date there has not been ample official information released concerning specific ports.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Qinzhou – Yangpu – Zhanjiang – Gaolan Port – Yantian – Nansha – Ho Chi Minh City (Vietnam) – Singapore – Yangon (Myanmar) – Palawan (Philippines) – Singapore – Qinzhou.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Qingdao – Shanghai – Ningbo – Manila (South) – Manila (North) – Qingdao.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Newport – Dalian – Qingdao – Shanghai – Xiamen – Hong Kong – Singapore – Klang Port (Malaysia) – Penang (Malaysia) – Singapore – Hong Kong – Xingang.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Shanghai – Newport – Dalian – Qingdao – Ningbo – Nansha – Jakarta (Indonesia) – Klang Port (Malaysia) – Singapore – Laem Chabang Port (Thailand) – Hong Kong – Shanghai.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Ningbo – Shanghai – Shekou – Sihanoukville (Cambodia) – Bangkok – Leam Chabang (Thailand) – Ningbo.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Qingdao – Shanghai – Ningbo – Singapore – Klang Port (Malaysia) – Karachi (Pakistan) – Mundra (India) – Colombo (Sri Lanka) – Singapore – Qingdao.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Shanghai – Ningbo – Shekou – Singapore – Port Klang (Malaysia) – Kolkata (India) – Pipavav (India) – Colombo (Sri Lanka) – Port Klang – Singapore – Ho Chi Minh City (Vietnam) – Hong Kong – Shanghai.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Shanghai – Ningbo – Kaohsiung – Xiamen – Shekou – Port Klang (Malaysia) – Alishan Port (UAE) – Umm Qasr (Iraq) – Port Klang – Kaohsiung – Shanghai.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Shanghai – Ningbo – Xiamen – Chiwan – Singapore – Djibouti (East Africa) – Jeddah (Saudi Arabia) – Sudan (Sudan) – Djibouti – Port Klang – Shanghai.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The MSR route to Europe will begin in China, pass through the Malacca Strait, follow Red Sea through the Suez Canal to the Mediterranean Sea, and visit ports in Greece, Italy, France, and Spain before returning to China.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The Maritime Silk Road has also an important role in the connection between East Africa and the Mediterranean region through the Suez Canal.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Of particular interest to China is the port of Piraeus in Athens, Greece, which Chinese Premier Li Keqiang stated "...can become China's gateway to Europe.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] " China is investing heavily in Athens in the port and infrastructure.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The Chinese Silk Road Initiative then led Europe to consider adapting the infrastructure to changing conditions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] In recent years there have been major investments from Italy, the EU, Germany and Hungary to develop Trieste with its rail connections to Central and Eastern Europe as a central European hub of the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] This also applies to the partial relocation of the flow of goods from the northern ports to the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] There are extensive intra-European infrastructure projects in place to adapt trade flows to current needs.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] This applies, for example, to the expansion of the Belgrade-Budapest railway line, the Brenner Base Tunnel and the connections on the Adriatic-Baltic and Adriatic-North Sea axes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] With regard to costs and environmental protection, in contrast to longer East Asian traffic via northwest Europe, the sea route through the Suez Canal to the Adriatic bridgehead of Trieste with its free trade zone shortens the transport of goods to Central and Eastern Europe by at least four days.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Experimental attempts are also being made to organize the movement of goods from China to Europe via the Northeast Passage through the polar sea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] There is already resistance from environmental protection organizations who fear significant interference in the sensitive ecosystems in the north.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] One of the most important ports in the Mediterranean is Valencia, Spain.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The port, in which many Chinese companies have settled, is to be provided with a free trade zone.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] There exist a number of unresolved territorial disputes in the South China Sea between China and ASEAN countries such as Brunei, Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines, and Vietnam.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Potential routes proposed for the MSR could contribute to increasing tensions over certain areas.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] However, some academics propose that the MSR initiative will provide a means for China to resolve these sovereignty-related conflicts by providing an opportunity for mutual gain.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] It has been suggested that the future of the MSR will be largely dictated by the economic conditions of the participating countries.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] The possibility exists that China may have to make financial contributions to other MSR countries who are experiencing poor economic conditions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] China will need to ensure that any loans allocated to these countries are spent appropriately.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Coordination on the national and subnational levels may be challenging for China.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] It has been stated that China's subnational actors – such as multinational corporations, provinces, cities, and towns – have a tendency to strongly prioritize their own interests above those of the nation and participate in government initiatives primarily to satisfy their own objectives.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] This could lead to inappropriate spending on projects outside the scope of China's national interests.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Gaining political approval from countries with different political systems could prove problematic for China.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Countries may be wary about joining the MSR initiative due to geopolitical and security factors.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] Concerns have been put forth regarding whether China will be able to receive India's cooperation and participating in bringing the initiative to fruition.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] India represents a strong economic force and may likely prefer to develop the Indian Ocean region's infrastructure itself rather than allow China to have any control over the region.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] While Chinese investment in India's underdeveloped maritime infrastructure could benefit India's economy greatly, India remains wary to accept such investment as the possibility exists that China is primarily attempting to expand its own territorial and economic interests.
[src:maritime-silk-road/21st-century-maritime-silk-road] India has also expressed circumspection in participating in a similar initiative, the Bangladesh – China – India – Myanmar economic corridor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The **Abydos boats** are the remnants of a group of ancient royal Egyptian ceremonial boats found at an archaeological site in Abydos, Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Discovered in 1991, excavation of the Abydos boats began in 2000 at which time fourteen boats were identified.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] They are located alongside the massive mudbrick structure known as Shunet El Zebib, attributed to the 2nd Dynasty Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Shunet El Zebib is one of several such "enclosure wall" constructions at this site dating back to the Early Dynastic Period, and is located nearly one mile from the royal cemetery of Umm El Qa'ab.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The University of Pennsylvania Museum and Yale University Expedition carried out the excavation of the Abydos boats.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Lines of mudbrick uncovered by blowing sand were first noticed in 1988 at a site a mile away from the royal tombs in Abydos.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] These brick remains were first thought to be just walls.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] However, it was later determined that they were the boundaries for more than a dozen ship burials from an early dynasty.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Each ship grave had its own brick boundary walls.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The outline of each grave was in the shape of a boat, and the surface of each was covered with mud plaster and whitewash.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Small boulders at the prow or stern of each grave represented anchors.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Because of the fragility of the boat remains, almost no excavation was done initially as the situation had to be carefully studied for future conservation.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] 10, which was slowly appearing due to apparent soil erosion, was the only boat that was initially investigated.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] For five days, archaeologists carefully examined the midsection of the ship.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] They uncovered wooden planks, disintegrated rope, and reed bundles.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Wood-eating ants had reduced much of the ship's hull to frass (ant excrement), but the frass had retained the shape of the original hull.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The midsection of this boat revealed the construction methods used and confirmed the oldest ‘planked’ constructed boat yet discovered.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The boat's construction revealed it had been constructed from the outside in, as there was no internal frame.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Averaging 75 ft long and 7–10 ft wide at their greatest width, these boats were only about two feet deep, with narrow prows and sterns.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Several boats were white-plastered, as were the Abydos tombs, and no.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Seams between planks were filled with reed bundles, reeds also covered the floor of each Abydos boat.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Without internal framing, some of these boats became twisted, as was unavoidable without an internal skeleton for support when out of the water.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The wood of the Abydos boats was local *Tamarix* – tamarisk, salt cedar – not cedar from Lebanon which was used for Khufu’s Solar Barque and favored for shipbuilding in Egypt in later dynasties.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Lebanon cedar was used for the poles and beams of the Umm el-Qa'ab tombs and had already been imported earlier; pigment residues hinted at bright colors.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] 29A cultural center.” This technology for ship construction persisted in Egypt for more than one thousand years and the standardization of this earliest phase of plank boat construction in Egypt is striking.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats were found in boat graves with their prows pointed towards the Nile.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Experts consider them to have been the royal boats intended for the pharaoh in the afterlife.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis that is about one mile from the Abydos boat graves where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are the predecessors of the great solar boats of later dynasties upon which the pharaoh joined the sun god Ra and together journeyed down the sacred Nile during the day.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] They would have had many of the important attributes and metaphors that were attached to the solar barques of later dynasties, and indeed perhaps should be called solar boats of an earlier design.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The Khufu ship, built for the Pharaoh Khufu – Cheops – ca.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] 2500 BC., is usually identified as the earliest solar barque.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] It was buried in a pit at the foot of the Great Pyramid at Giza.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The Abydos boat graves were adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] 2675 B.C.) Pharaoh Khasekhemwy at Abydos which is eight miles from the Nile.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis at Abydos where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] However, these boat graves were established earlier than late in Dynasty II, perhaps for the afterlife journeys of Hor-Aha, the first king (ca.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] 2920–2770) of the First Dynasty of Egypt, or Pharaoh Djer also of Dynasty I.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Two more recently located mortuary discoveries have been identified as those of King Aha, who may have been the son of the famous King Narmer, to whom the first unification of Upper and Lower Egypt is often attributed.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are not the only find of First Dynasty ships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Nineteen boat burials were found at Helwan, but only four of these finds were published.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Six boat graves were found at Saqqara by Walter Bryan Emery and four of these finds were published.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Finally two full-sized model boats made out of clay are known from Abu Roash Hill.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Helwan (a suburb of Cairo on eastern side of Nile) contain a huge cemetery field 20 km south of Cairo adjoining Saqqara in which at least 10,000 tombs have been cataloged.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] The size of Helwan indicates a very large population for Early Dynastic Memphis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] Almost all the tombs date from Dynasty 0 through the Third Dynasty.
[src:maritime-silk-road/abydos-boats] There are 19 elite tombs where 1st Dynasty funeral boat burials have been discovered that resemble those at Abydos, but little published information is available.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The city is one of Mexico's oldest beach resorts, coming into prominence in the 1940s through the 1960s as a getaway for Hollywood stars and millionaires.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco was once a popular tourist resort, but due to a massive upsurge in gang violence and homicide numbers since 2014, Acapulco no longer attracts many foreign tourists, and most now only come from within Mexico itself.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It is both the ninth deadliest city in Mexico and the tenth-deadliest city in the world as of 2022; the US government has warned its citizens not to travel there.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 2016 there were 918 murders, and the homicide rate was one of the highest in the world: 103 in every 100,000.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In September 2018, the city's entire police force was disarmed by the military, due to suspicions that it had been infiltrated by drug gangs.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The name "Acapulco, Guerrero" comes from Nahuatl language *Aca-pōl-co*, and means "where the reeds were destroyed or washed away" or "at the big reeds", which inspired the city's seal, which is an Aztec-type glyph showing two hands breaking reeds.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The "de Juárez" was added to the official name in 1885 to honor Benito Juárez, former president of Mexico (1806–1872).
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The island and municipality of Capul, in the Philippines, derives its name from Acapulco, Guerrero.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco, Guerrero was the eastern end of the trans-Pacific sailing route from Acapulco to Manila, in what was then a Spanish colony.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] By the 8th century, around the Acapulco Bay area, there was a small culture which would first be dominated by the Olmecs, then by a number of others during the pre-Hispanic period before it ended in the 1520s.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] At Acapulco Bay itself, there were two Olmec sites, one by Playa Larga and the other on a hill known as *El Guitarrón*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Olmec influence caused the small spread-out villages here to coalesce into larger entities and build ceremonial centers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Later, Teotihuacan influence came to the area via Cuernavaca and Chilpancingo.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Then Mayan influence arrived from the Isthmus of Tehuantepec and through what is now Oaxaca.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This history is known through the archaeological artifacts that have been found here, especially at *Playa Hornos, Pie de la Cuesta*, and *Tambuco*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the 11th century, new waves of migration of Nahuas, including the *Coixcas*, came through here.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] These people were the antecedents of the Aztecs.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the later 15th century, after four years of military struggle, Acapulco became part of the Aztec Empire during the reign of Ahuizotl (1486–1502).
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It was annexed to a tributary province centered at Tecpan de Galeana.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] However, this was only transitory, as the Aztecs could only establish an unorganized military post at the city's outskirts.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The city was in territory under control of the *Yopis*, who continued defending it and living there until the arrival of the Spanish in the 1520s.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There are two stories about how Acapulco bay was discovered by Europeans.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The first states that two years after the Spanish conquest of the Aztec Empire, Hernán Cortés sent explorers west to find gold.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The explorers had subdued this area after 1523, and Captain Saavedra Cerón was authorized by Cortés to found a settlement here.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The other states that the bay was discovered on December 13, 1526, by a small ship named the El Tepache Santiago captained by Santiago Guevara.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The first encomendero was established in 1525 at *Cacahuatepec*, which is still part of the modern Acapulco municipality.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1531, a number of Spaniards, most notably Juan Rodriguez de Villafuerte, left the Oaxaca coast and founded the village of Villafuerte where the city of Acapulco now stands.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Villafuerte was unable to subdue the local native peoples, and this eventually resulted in the Yopa Rebellion in the region of *Cuautepec*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Hernán Cortés was obligated to send Vasco Porcayo to negotiate with the indigenous people giving concessions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The province of Acapulco became the encomendero of Rodriguez de Villafuerte who received taxes in the form of cocoa, cotton and corn.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Cortés established Acapulco as a major port by the early 1530s, with the first major road between Mexico City and the port constructed by 1531.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The wharf, named Marqués, was constructed by 1533 between Bruja Point and Diamond Point.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Soon after, the area was made an "alcadia" (major province or town).
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Spanish trade with the Far East gave Acapulco a prominent place in the economy of New Spain.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1550, thirty Spanish families were sent from Mexico City to establish a permanent base of European residents.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Galleons began arriving from Asia in 1565, and the Manila-Acapulco trade route made Acapulco the second most important port in New Spain after Veracruz.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1573, the Crown granted a monopoly on trade with Manila and Acapulco became a center of communication between Europe, Asia, and the Americas.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] On January 25, 1614, a delegation led by samurai Hasekura Tsunenaga, which included over one hundred Japanese Christians as well as twenty-two samurai under the shōgun Tokugawa Ieyasu, arrived from Japan to Acapulco as part of a mission to form closer relations with Catholic Europe.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] A fight soon broke out in which a Japanese samurai stabbed a Spanish colonial soldier in Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This was witnessed and recorded by historian Chimalpahin, who was the grandson of an Aztec nobleman.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Some of Tsunenaga's delegation would stay and marry with the locals.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The galleon trade made its yearly run from the mid-16th century until the early 19th.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The luxury items it brought to New Spain attracted the attention of English and Dutch pirates, such as Francis Drake, Henry Morgan and Thomas Cavendish, who called it "The Black Ship".
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] A Dutch fleet invaded Acapulco in 1615, destroying much of the town before being driven off.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Fort of San Diego was built the following year to protect the port and the cargo of arriving ships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The fort was destroyed by an earthquake in 1776 and was rebuilt between 1778 and 1783.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] At the beginning of the 19th century, King Charles IV declared Acapulco a Ciudad Official and it became an essential part of the Spanish Crown.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] However, not long after, the Mexican War of Independence began.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1810, José María Morelos y Pavón attacked and burnt down the city, after he defeated royalist commander Francisco Parés at the Battle of Tres Palos.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The independence of Mexico in 1821 ended the run of the Manila Galleon.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco's importance as a port recovered during the California Gold Rush in the mid-19th-century, with ships going to and coming from Panama stopping here.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This city was besieged on April 19, 1854 by Antonio López de Santa Anna after Guerrero's leadership had rebelled by issuing the Plan de Ayutla.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] After an unsuccessful week of fighting, Santa Anna retreated.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1911, revolutionary forces took over the main plaza of Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1920, the Prince of Wales (the future King Edward VIII) visited the area.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Impressed by what he saw, he recommended the place to his compatriots in Europe, making it popular with the elite there.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Much of the original hotel and trading infrastructure was built by a businessman named Albert B.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Pullen from Corrigan, Texas, in the area now known as Old Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1933, Carlos Barnard started the first section of *Hotel El Mirador*, with 12 rooms on the cliffs of La Quebrada.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Albert Pullen built the *Las Americas Hotel*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the late 1930s, "La Fraccionadora de Acapulco, S.A." (FASA), consisting of William Pullen, Anacleto Martínez, Juan M.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Salcedo, and Wolf Schoenburg, who was especially instrumental, started tourism development in earnest.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the mid-1940s, the first commercial wharf and warehouses were built.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the early 1950s, President Miguel Alemán Valdés upgraded the port's infrastructure, installing electrical lines, drainage systems, roads and the first highway to connect the port with Mexico City.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The economy grew and foreign investment increased with it.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] During the 1950s, Acapulco became the fashionable place for millionaire Hollywood stars such as Elizabeth Taylor, Frank Sinatra, Eddie Fisher and Brigitte Bardot.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The 1963 Hollywood movie *Fun in Acapulco*, starring Elvis Presley, is set in Acapulco although the filming took place in the United States.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Former swing musician Teddy Stauffer, the so-called "Mister Acapulco", was a hotel manager ("Villa Vera", "Casablanca"), who attracted many celebrities to Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] From a population of only 4,000 or 5,000 in the 1940s, by the early 1960s, Acapulco had a population of about 50,000.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1958, the Diocese of Acapulco was created by Pope Pius XII.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] During the 1960s and 1970s, new hotel resorts were built, and accommodation and transport were made cheaper.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It was no longer necessary to be a millionaire to spend a holiday in Acapulco; the foreign and Mexican middle class could now afford to travel here.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] However, as more hotels were built in the south part of the bay, the old hotels of the 1950s lost their grandeur.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] For the 1968 Summer Olympics in neighboring Mexico City, Acapulco hosted the sailing (then yachting) events.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the 1970s, there was a significant expansion of the port.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Miss Universe 1978 pageant took place in the city.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1983, singer-songwriter Juan Gabriel wrote the song "Amor eterno", which pays homage to Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The song was first and most famously recorded by Rocío Dúrcal.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Additionally, Acapulco is the hometown of actress, singer, and comedian Aída Pierce, who found fame during the 1980s, 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 1993, a section of Mexican Federal Highway 95D, nicknamed *Autopista del Sol* was built, crossing the mountains between Mexico City and Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The journey takes only about three-and-a-half hours, making Acapulco a favorite weekend destination for Mexico City inhabitants.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The port continued to grow and in 1996, a new private company, API Acapulco, was created to manage operations.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This consolidated operations and now Acapulco is the major port for car exports to the Pacific.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The city was devastated by Hurricane Pauline in 1997.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The storm stranded tourists and left more than 100 dead in the city.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Most of the victims were from the shantytowns built on steep hillsides that surround the city.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Other victims were swept away by the winds and waves.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The main road, Avenida Costera, became a fast-moving river of sludge three feet (0.91 m) in depth.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the 21st century, the Mexican drug war has had a negative effect on tourism in Acapulco as rival drug cartels fight each other for the Guerrero coast route that brings drugs from South America as well as soldiers that have been fighting the cartels since 2006.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] A major gun battle between 18 gunmen and soldiers took place in the summer of 2009 in the Old Acapulco seaside area, lasting hours and killing 16 of the gunmen and two soldiers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This came after the 2009 swine flu pandemic outbreak earlier in the year nearly paralyzed the Mexican economy, forcing hotels to give discounts to bring tourists back.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] However, hotel occupancy for 2009 was down five percent from the year before.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The death of Arturo Beltrán Leyva in December 2009 resulted in infighting among different groups within the Beltrán Leyva cartel.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Gang violence continued to plague Acapulco through 2010 and into 2011, most notably with at least 15 dying in drug-related violence on March 13, 2010, and another 15 deaths on January 8, 2011.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Among the first incident's dead were six members of the city police and the brother of an ex-mayor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the second incident, the headless bodies of 15 young men were found dumped near the Plaza Sendero shopping center.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] On August 20, 2011, Mexican authorities reported that five headless bodies were found in Acapulco, three of which were placed in the city's main tourist area and two of which were cut into multiple pieces.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] On February 4, 2013, six Spanish men were tied up and robbed and the six Spanish women with them were gang-raped by five masked gunmen who stormed a beach house on the outskirts of Acapulco, though after these accusations, none of the victims decided to press charges.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] On September 28, 2014, Mexican politician Braulio Zaragoza was gunned down at the *El Mirador* hotel in the city.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] He was the leader of the conservative opposition National Action Party (PAN) in southern Guerrero state.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Several politicians have been targeted by drug cartels operating in the area.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Investigations are under way, but no arrests have yet been made as of September 29.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The insecurity due to individuals involved with drug cartels has cost the city of Acapulco its popularity among national and international tourists.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 2018, the Mexican Armed Forces entered the city, placing it under occupation.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The police department was disarmed after allegations of the latter being linked to the cartels.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] On October 25, 2023, Hurricane Otis, a Category 5 hurricane with 1-minute sustained winds of 160 mph (260 km/h), caused widespread devastation throughout the city while making landfall nearby.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Hurricane John struck Acapulco and Mexico's Pacific coast in late September 2024 as a Category 3 hurricane, delivering powerful winds and extreme rainfall that led to widespread flooding and significant damage.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco experienced nearly one meter of rainfall, resulting in submerged neighborhoods and serious disruptions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Roads became impassable due to landslides, and extensive power outages left tens of thousands without electricity across Guerrero and Oaxaca.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Around 40,000 homes were damaged impacting over 150,000 residents.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The city, located on the Pacific coast of Mexico in the state of Guerrero, is classified as one of the state's seven regions, dividing the rest of the Guerrero coast into the Costa Grande and the Costa Chica.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Forty percent of the municipality is mountainous terrain; another forty percent is semi-flat; and the other twenty percent is flat.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Elevation varies from sea level to 1,699 metres (5,574 feet).
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The highest peaks are *Potrero, San Nicolas*, and *Alto Camarón*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] One major river runs through the municipality, the *Papagayo*, along with a number of *arroyos* (streams).
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There are also two small lagoons, Tres Palos and Coyuca, along with a number of thermal springs.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco features a tropical wet and dry climate (Köppen: Aw): hot with distinct wet and dry seasons, with more even temperatures between seasons than resorts farther north in Mexico, but this varies depending on altitude.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The warmest areas are next to the sea where the city is.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Pacific hurricanes and tropical storms are threats from May through November; notably, the city was struck directly by Category 5 Hurricane Otis on October 25, 2023, which caused extensive damage.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The forested area tends to lose leaves during the winter dry season, with evergreen pines in the highest elevations.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Fauna consists mostly of deer, small mammals, a wide variety of both land and seabirds, and marine animals such as turtles.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Oddly enough, January, its coolest month, also features its all-time record high.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The temperature of the sea is quite stable, with lows of 82 °F (28 °C) between January – March, and a high of 86 °F (30 °C) in August.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] These sea surface temperatures are much warmer than those further north along the Pacific coast, and indeed warmer than most places further south, as sea surface temperatures begin to decline with proximity to the Southern Hemisphere's Humboldt Current.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] As the seat of a municipality, the city of Acapulco is the government authority for over 700 other communities, which together have a territory of 1,880.60 km2.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This municipality borders the municipalities of Chilpancingo, Juan R Escudero (Tierra Colorada), San Marcos, Coyuca de Benítez with the Pacific Ocean to the south.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The metropolitan area is made up of the municipalities of Acapulco de Juárez and Coyuca de Benitez.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The area has a population (as of 2005) of 786,830.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] For the names and terms of some Acapulco mayors, you can check a List of municipal presidents of Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It is considered the twenty-second most populous city in Mexico and the tenth most populous metropolitan area in Mexico.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It is also the city with the highest concentration of population of the homonymous municipality, representing 85.25 percent of the 789,971 inhabitants.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the 2020 census of 658,609 people where counted in the locality and 779,566 in the municipality of Acapulco, a small drop from the last census.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The metropolitan area of Acapulco is made up of six towns in the municipality of Acapulco de Juárez and four in the municipality of Coyuca de Benítez.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Tourism is the main economic activity of the municipality and most of this is centered on Acapulco Bay.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] About seventy-three percent of the municipality's population is involved in commerce, most of it related to tourism and the port.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Mining and manufacturing employ less than twenty percent and only about five percent is dedicated to agriculture.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Industrial production is limited mostly to bottling, milk products, cement products, and ice and energy production.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Agricultural products include tomatoes, corn, watermelon, beans, green chili peppers, and melons.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco is one of Mexico's oldest coastal tourist destinations, reaching prominence in the 1950s as the place where Hollywood stars and millionaires vacationed on the beach in an exotic locale.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In modern times, tourists in Acapulco have been facing problems with corrupt local police who steal money by extortion and intimidate visitors with threats of jail.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The city is divided into three tourist areas.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Traditional Acapulco is the old part of the port, where hotels like Hotel Los Flamingos, owned by personalities Johnny Weissmuller and John Wayne are located, is on the northern end of the bay.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Anchored by attractions such as the beaches of Caleta and Caletilla, the cliff divers of La Quebrada, and the city square, known as *El Zocalo*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The heyday of this part of Acapulco ran from the late 1930s until the 1960s, with development continuing through the 1980s.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This older section of town now caters to a mostly middle-class, almost exclusively Mexican clientele, while the glitzier newer section caters to the Mexican upper classes, many of whom never venture into the older, traditional part of town.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco Dorado had its development between the 1950s and the 1970s, and is about 25 minutes from the Acapulco International Airport.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It is the area that presents the most tourist influx in the port, runs through much of the Acapulco bay, from Icacos, passing through Costera Miguel Aleman Avenue, which is the main one, to Papagayo Park.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Starting at the Scenic Highway in Las Brisas, it includes Puerto Marqués and Punta Diamante and extends to Barra Vieja Beach.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It is 10 minutes from the Acapulco International Airport.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In this area, all along *Boulevard de las Naciones*, almost all transportation is by car, limousine or golf cart.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco's reputation of a high-energy party town and the nightlife have long been draws of the city for tourists.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] From November to April, luxury liners stop here daily and include ships such as the MS *Queen Victoria*, the MS *Rotterdam*, *Crystal Harmony*, and all the Princess line ships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Despite Acapulco's international fame, most of its visitors are from central Mexico, especially the affluent from Mexico City.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco is one of the embarkation ports for the Mexican cruise line Ocean Star Cruises.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] For the Christmas season of 2009, Acapulco received 470,000 visitors, most of whom are Mexican nationals, adding 785 million pesos to the economy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Eighty percent arrive by land and eighteen percent by air.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The area has over 25,000 condominiums, most of which function as second homes for their Mexican owners.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco is still popular with Mexican celebrities and the wealthy, such as Luis Miguel and Plácido Domingo, who maintain homes there.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Over the years, a number of problems have plagued Acapulco, especially in the bay and the older sections of the city.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The large number of wandering vendors on the beaches, who offer everything from newspapers to massages, are a recognized problem.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It is a bother to tourists who simply want to relax on the beach, but the government says it is difficult to eradicate, as there is a lot of unemployment and poverty in the city.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Around the city are many small shantytowns that cling to the mountainsides, populated by migrants who have come to the city looking for work.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the last decade, drug-related violence has caused massive problems for the local tourism trade.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Another problem is the garbage that has accumulated in the bay.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Although 60.65 tons have recently been extracted from the bays of Acapulco and nearby Zihuatanejo, more needs to be done.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Most of trash removal during the off seasons is done on the beaches and in the waters closest to them.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] However, the center of the bay is not touched.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The reason trash winds up in the bay is that it is common in the city to throw it in streets, rivers and the bay itself.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The most common items cleaned out of the bay are beer bottles and car tires.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco has seen some success in this area, having several beaches receiving the high "blue flag" certifications for cleanliness and water quality.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The following are typical dishes from the region: Relleno is baked pork with a variety of vegetables and fruits such as potatoes, raisins, carrots and chiles.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It is eaten with bread called *bolillo*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Pozole is a soup with a salsa base (it can be white, red or green), hominy, meat that can be either pork or chicken and it is accompanied with *antojitos* (snacks) like tostadas, tacos and tamales.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This dish is served as part of a weekly Thursday event in the city and the state, with many restaurants offering the meal with special entertainment, from bands to dancers to celebrity impersonators.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco's main attraction is its nightlife, as it has been for many decades.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Nightclubs change names and owners frequently.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] For example, Baby 'O has been open to the national and international public since 1976 and different celebrities have visited their installations such as Mexican singer Luis Miguel, Bono from U2 and Sylvester Stallone.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Another nightclub is Palladium, located in the Escénica Avenue, the location gives the nightclub a view of the Santa Lucia Bay at night.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Informal lobby or poolside cocktail bars often offer free live entertainment.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In addition, there is the beach bar zone, where younger crowds go.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] These are located along the Costera road, face the ocean and feature techno or alternative rock.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Most are concentrated between the Fiesta Americana and Continental Plaza hotels.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] These places tend to open earlier and have more informal dress.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There is a bungee jump in this area as well.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Another attraction at Acapulco is the La Quebrada Cliff Divers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The tradition started in the 1930s when young men casually competed against each other to see who could dive from the highest point into the sea below.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Eventually, locals began to ask for tips for those coming to see the men dive.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Today the divers are professionals, diving from heights of 40 metres (130 feet) into an inlet that is only 7 metres (23 ft) wide and 4 metres (13 ft) deep, after praying first at a shrine to the Virgin of Guadalupe.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] On the evening before December 12, the feast day of this Virgin, freestyle cliff divers jump into the sea to honor her.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Dives range from the simple to the complicated and end with the "Ocean of Fire" when the sea is lit with gasoline, making a circle of flames which the diver aims for.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The spectacle can be seen from a public area which charges a small fee or from the Hotel Plaza Las Glorias/El Mirador from its bar or restaurant terrace.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There are a number of beaches in the Acapulco Bay and the immediate coastline.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the bay proper there are the La Angosta (in the Quebrada), Caleta, Caletilla, Dominguillo, Tlacopanocha, Hornos, Hornitos, Honda, Tamarindo, Condesa, Guitarrón, Icacos, Playuela, Playuelilla and Playa del Secreto.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the adjoining, smaller Bay of Puerto Marqués there is Pichilingue, Las Brisas, and Playa Roqueta.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Facing open ocean just northwest of the bays is Pie de la Cuesta and southeast are Playa Revolcadero, Playa Aeromar, Playa Encantada and Barra Vieja.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Two lagoons are in the area, Coyuca to the northwest of Acapulco Bay and Tres Palos to the southeast.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Both lagoons have mangroves and offer boat tours.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Tres Palos also has sea turtle nesting areas which are protected.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In addition to sunbathing, the beaches around the bay offer a number of services, such as boat rentals, boat tours, horseback riding, scuba diving and other aquatic sports.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] One popular cruise is from Caletilla Beach to Roqueta Island, which has places to snorkel, have lunch, and a lighthouse.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There is also an underwater statue of the Virgin of Guadalupe here, created in 1958 by Armando Quesado in memory of a group of divers who died here.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Many of the scuba-diving tours come to this area as well, where there are sunken ships, sea mountains, and cave rock formations.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Another popular activity is deep-sea fishing.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Fish caught here have weighed between 89 and 200 pounds.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Sailfish are so plentiful that boat captains have been known to bet with a potential customer that if he does not catch anything, the trip is free.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the old part of the city, there is a traditional main square called the Zócalo, lined with shade trees, cafés and shops.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] At the north end of the square is *Nuestra Señora de la Soledad* cathedral, with blue onion-shaped domes and Byzantine towers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The building was originally constructed as a movie set, but was later adapted into a church.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco's most historic building is the Fort of San Diego, located east of the main square and originally built in 1616 to protect the city from pirate attacks.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The fort was built by a Dutch engineer and finished in 1617 then destroyed in 1776 by an earthquake.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It was rebuilt by 1783 and this is the building that can be seen today, unchanged except for renovations done to it in 2000.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Parts of the moats remain as well as the five bulwarks and the battlements.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Today the fort serves as the Museo Histórico de Acapulco (Acapulco Historical Museum), which shows the port's history from the pre-Hispanic period until independence.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] For many years tourists could ride around the city in colorful horse-drawn carriages known as *calandrias*, but the practice ended in February 2020 due to concerns about mistreatment of the animals.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The El Rollo Acapulco is a sea-life and aquatic park located on Costera Miguel Aleman.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It offers wave pools, water slides and water toboggans.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There are also dolphin shows daily and a swim with dolphins program.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Another place that is popular with children is the *Parque Papagayo*: a large family park which has a life-sized replica of a Spanish galleon, three artificial lakes, an aviary, a skating rink, rides, go-karts and more.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Dolores Olmedo House is located in the traditional downtown of Acapulco and is noted for the murals by Diego Rivera that adorn it.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Olmedo and Rivera had been friend since Olmedo was a child and Rivera spent the last two years of his life here.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] During that time, he painted nearly nonstop and created the outside walls with tile mosaics, featuring Aztec deities such as Quetzalcoatl.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The interior of the home is covered in murals.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The home is not a museum, so only the outside murals can be seen by the public.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There is a small museum called *Casa de la Máscara* (House of Masks) which is dedicated to masks, most of them from Mexico, but there are examples from many parts of the world.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The collection contains about one thousand examples and is divided into seven rooms called Masks of the World, Mexico across History, The Huichols and the Jaguar, Alebrijes, Dances of Guerrero, Devils and Death, Identity and Fantasy, and Afro-Indian masks.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Botanical Garden of Acapulco is a tropical garden located on lands owned by the Universidad Loyola del Pacífico.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Most of the plants here are native to the region, and many, such as the Peltogyne mexicana or purple stick tree, are in danger of extinction.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] One cultural event that is held yearly in Acapulco is the *Festival Internacional de la Nao*, which takes place in the Fort of San Diego, located near the Zócalo in downtown of the city.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Festival honors the remembrance of the city's interaction and trades with Oriental territories which started back in the Sixteenth Century.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Nao Festival consists of cultural activities with the support of organizations and embassies from India, China, Japan, Philippines, Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The variety of events go from film projections, musical interpretations and theatre to gastronomical classes, some of the events are specifically for kids.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The annual French Festival takes place throughout Acapulco city and offers a multitude of events that cement cultural links between Mexico and France.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The main features are a fashion show and a gourmet food fair.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Cinépolis Galerías Diana and the Teatro Juan Ruíz de Alarcón present French and French literary figures who give talks on their specialised subjects.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Even some of the local nightclubs feature French DJs.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Other festivals celebrated here include Carnival, the feast of San Isidro Labrador on 15 May, and in November, a crafts and livestock fair called the Nao de China.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There are a number of golf courses in Acapulco including the Acapulco Princess and the Pierre Marqués course, the latter designed by Robert Trent Jones in 1972 for the World Cup Golf Tournament.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Mayan Palace course was designed by Pedro Guericia and an economical course called the Club de Golf Acapulco is near the convention center.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The most exclusive course is that of the Tres Vidas Golf Club, designed by Robert von Hagge.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] It is located next to the ocean and is home to flocks of ducks and other birds.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Another famous sport tournament that has been held in Acapulco since 1993 is the Mexican Open tennis tournament, an ATP 500 event that currently takes place at the Arena GNP Seguros.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Initially it was played in clay courts but it changed to hard court.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The event has gained popularity within the passing of the years, attracting some of the top tennis players in the world including Novak Djokovic, Rafael Nadal and Marin Cilic.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Acapulco also has a bullring, called the Plaza de Toros, near Caletilla Beach.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The season runs during the winter and is called the Fiesta Brava.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Before 2010, over 100,000 American teenagers and young adults traveled to resort areas and balnearios throughout Mexico during spring break each year.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The main reason students head to Mexico is the drinking age of 18 years (versus 21 for the United States), something that has been marketed by tour operators along with the sun and ocean.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This has become attractive since the 1990s, especially since more traditional spring break places such as Daytona Beach, Florida, have enacted restrictions on drinking and other behaviors.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This legislation has pushed spring break tourism to various parts of Mexico, with Acapulco as one of the top destinations.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, Cancún had been favored as the spring break destination of choice.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] However, Cancún has taken some steps to control the reckless behavior associated with the event, and students have been looking for someplace new.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] This led many more to choose Acapulco, in spite of the fact that for many travelers, the flight is longer and more expensive than to Cancún.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Many were attracted by the glitzy hotels on the south side and Acapulco's famous nightlife.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 2008, 22,500 students came to Acapulco for spring break.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Hotels did not get that many in 2009, due mostly to the economic situation in the United States, and partially because of scares of drug-related violence.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In February 2009, the US State Department issued a travel alert directed at college students planning spring break trips to Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The warning—a result of violent activity springing from Mexico's drug cartel débâcle—took college campuses by storm, with some schools going so far as to warn their students about the risks of travel to Mexico over spring break.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Bill O'Reilly devoted a segment of his show, *The O'Reilly Factor*, to urge students to stay away from Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In June 2009, a number of incidents occurred between the drug cartel and the government.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] These included coordinated attacks on police headquarters and open battles in the streets, involving large-caliber weapons and grenades.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] However, no incidents of violence against travelers on spring break were reported.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Nine passenger airlines, including four international ones, fly to Acapulco International Airport.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In the city, there are many buses and taxi services one can take to get from place to place, but most of the locals choose to walk to their destinations.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] However, an important mode of transportation is the government-subsidized 'Colectivo' cab system.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] These cabs cost 13 pesos per person to ride, but they are not private.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The driver will pick up more passengers as long as seats are available, and will transport them to their destination based on first-come, first-served rules.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The colectivos each travel a designated area of the city, the three main ones being Costera, Colosio, Coloso, or a mixture of the three.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Coloso cabs travel mainly to old Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Colosio cabs travel through most of the tourist area of Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Costera cabs drive up and down the coast of Acapulco, where most of the hotels for visitors are located, but which includes some of old Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Drivers have discretion over destinations; some are willing to travel to the other designated areas, especially during slow periods of the day.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The bus system is highly complex and can be rather confusing to an outsider.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] As far as transportation goes, it is the cheapest form, other than walking, in Acapulco.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The most expensive buses have air conditioning, while the cheaper buses do not.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] For tourists, the Acapulco city government has established a system of yellow buses with Acapulco painted on the side of them.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] These buses are not for tourists only, but are certainly the nicest and most uniform of the bus systems.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] These buses travel the tourist section of Acapulco, driving up and down the coast.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] There are buses with specific routes and destinations, generally written on their windshields or shouted out by a barker riding in the front seat.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Perhaps the most unusual thing about the privately operated buses is the fact that they are all highly decorated and personalized, with decals and home-made interior designs that range from comic book scenes, to pornography, and even to "Hello Kitty" themes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The bus network was simplified on 25 June 2016 with the implementation of the Acabús.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The bus rapid transit system spans 36.2 kilometres (22.5 miles), with 16 stations spread throughout the city of Acapulco along five routes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Boarding is sped by prepayment at stations.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] In 2014, the idea to nominate the Manila-Acapulco Galleon Trade Route was initiated by the Mexican ambassador to UNESCO with the Filipino ambassador to UNESCO.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] An Experts' Roundtable Meeting was held at the University of Santo Tomas (UST) on April 23, 2015, as part of the preparation of the Philippines for the possible transnational nomination of the Manila-Acapulco Galleon Trade Route to the World Heritage List.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The nomination will be made jointly with Mexico.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The following are the experts and the topics they discussed during the roundtable meeting: Dr.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Bolunia on Shipyards in the Bicol Region; Mr.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Sheldon Clyde Jago-on, Bobby Orillaneda, and Ligaya Lacsina on Underwater Archaeology; Dr.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Leovino Garcia on Maps and Cartography; Fr.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Rene Javellana, S.J. on Fortifications in the Philippines; Felice Sta.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Fernando Zialcita on Textile; and Regalado Trota Jose on Historical Dimension.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The papers presented and discussed during the roundtable meeting will be synthesized into a working document to establish the route's Outstanding Universal Value.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] The Mexican side reiterated that they will also follow suit with the preparations for the route's nomination.
[src:maritime-silk-road/acapulco] Spain has also backed the nomination of the Manila-Acapulco Trade Route in the UNESCO World Heritage Site list and has also suggested the Archives of the Manila-Acapulco Galleons to be nominated as part of a separate UNESCO list, the UNESCO Memory of the World Register.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The **Achaemenid navy** (Old Persian: 𐎴𐎠𐎺 *nāva*) was the principal naval force of the Achaemenid Empire which existed between 525 BC and 330 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] In Old Persian, the written language of Achaemenid inscriptions, the word used to refer to the 'navy' or 'fleet' was "*nāva*", a noun in plural feminine nominative form.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] It is of the same root of Indo-European for words such as "navy" and "navigate".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] In modern usage of Persian language, the word has retained its form and meaning (lit.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] No relevant primary documents have been found about it, nor have any ruins of Persian naval installations or remains of ships been excavated.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] While independent Persian tradition is lost, all we know about the Achaemenid navy is recorded by ancient Greek historians like Herodotus.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Scholars categorize the record of operation of the navy to two distinct periods from 525 to 479, and from 479 to 330 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Cambyses founded the navy for conquest of Egypt in the Battle of Pelusium.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] After him, Darius I deployed the navy to strengthen dominance over the coast of Asia Minor, as well as its adjacent islands.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] During reign of Darius, Persians captured Samos (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] 517 BC), conquered Thrace, waged war on Scythia (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] 512 BC), and suppressed rebellions started in 500 BC, leading to the Battle of Lade (494 BC).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The navy had lost its presence in the Aegean Sea, and its strength was reduced.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] 468 BC), the Persians were defeated and lost 200 ships according to the account of Thucydides.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The next significant defeat occurred in c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] 450 BC, when they lost a war in Cyprus (near modern-day Larnaca).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The creation the organization, infrastructure, and financial basis of the Achaemenid navy is attributed to Darius I.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The coasts of Phoenicia, as well as Cyprus and Cilicia, always played a strategic role in the Achaemenid navy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Strabo and Herodotus mentioned two central bases for the navy: one in Cilicia and the other in Kyme–Phocaea (both located in modern-day Turkey).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Centers that trained crew for vessels were isolated from the central bases.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The Cilician base was heavily guarded by a large number of troops, whose payments were financed by the local tributes in that satrapy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] It is likely that Acco served as the third main base.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] According to Kaveh Farrokh, the first naval headquarters that hosted high command of the navy was located along the Shatt al-Arab, where it leads to the Persian Gulf (located in the modern-day Khuzestan Province of Iran).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] However, Cilicia was the main base and was always ready for deployment because unlike Shatt al-Arab, it was intended for power projection.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Smaller squadrons were stationed elsewhere, like those of Sidon and Halicarnassus, as well as Samos.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] An important base was a shipyard located at Tripolis, where Lebanese timber were nearby.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The Nile valley also served as a strategic base of operation, when Egypt was a satrapy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid settlements like Bahrain, Oman, Yemen and the Indian subcontinent were regular destinations for naval ships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] It is thought likely that bases existed in Abdera and Myus, though this is uncertain.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces had an active presence in the Black Sea, the Aegean Sea, the Mediterranean Sea and the Persian Gulf among others.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] They operated patrols in river or littoral environments like Shatt al-Arab and Euphrates in Mesopotamia, Nile in Egypt and Sind in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The command hierarchy of the navy is not certain, but Greek sources indicate that high commanders were selected from the imperial aristocracy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] There are reports of commanders of ships, and commanding officers of fleets with various non-Persians backgrounds, such as those of Carians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Commanders of Greek origin are also reported to have served in the navy, including even one Athenian.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Almost nothing is known about sailors of lower rank.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] In the wake of creating the navy, Persians hired Phoenician rowers and sailors, but later recruited from other subject peoples.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The marines standing in the forces were either Persians, Medes, or Scythians.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The servicemen were probably employed with full payment, because lengthy deployments imposed a drastic change to their communities especially if it included one or two harvests.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The first Achaemenid naval vessels, which were built at Phoenician shipyards, measured 40 meters (130 ft) in length and 6 meters (20 ft) width, and were capable of carrying 300 troops at best.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] According to Christopher Tuplin, Cypriot ships "appear a significant element in Persian fleets on various occasions".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The Persians were the first nation to use triremes in significant numbers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The first large trireme was commissioned by Cambyses.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] By 490 BC, the backbone of the fleet was consisted of triremes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Some triremes were modified as troopers, as well as some for carrying horses and supplies or building bridges.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Persian triremes differed from those of the Greek, and used Phoenician design.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The third level of rowers in Greek vessels was accommodated by adding a outrigger, but the Persians added to the height of the compartment instead.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] They reportedly were 110 feet (34 m) to 120 feet (37 m) long and had a beam of 15 feet (4.6 m).
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The ships were most likely capable of reaching 12 knots (22 km/h) under good sailing conditions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] They could reach full speed in 30 seconds from a dead stop.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Equipped with one mast with square sail, the triremes had rudders made up of two bladed oars, one on each side of stern, united by a crossbar.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The ram was made out of bronze, and was long and tapered to a single point.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The metal rams were designed to slice into the hulls of enemy ships after an impact.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Equipment included grappling hooks (used to catch and halt enemy ships) and two mangonels, the latter throwing stones or flammable projectiles.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] A typical Persian trireme is reported to have had 170 rowers, with the upper file carrying 62, and the middle and lower files each 54.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] In addition to the rowers, other personnel aboard triremes included 14 marines and some spare rowers and oars in case they were needed.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] In 480 BC, each trireme carried 200 men and 30 marines, according to Herodotus.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Triremes were too crowded to store their own supplies, and relied on support vessels for food and water.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] It was normal for the crew to disembark in the evening for eating and sleep.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Achaemenid navy later used more advanced vessels like quinqueremes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Other types of vessel in the fleet were triaconters, penteconters and light boats.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Smaller vessels used for river patrols could carry a maximum of 100–200 troops.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The navy operated a large number of vessels used to carry food and other supplies, which commonly had a displacement of 100 to 150 tons, at the time they invaded Egypt in 373 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Ships capable of carrying 350 to 500 tons were also used in significant numbers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] They also had horse transporters (*hippagogoi*) specifically built for this purpose, that could easily carry 30 horses.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Persian horse transport ships were good sailing ships that took advantage of the favorable winds, according to Anthony J.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Papalas, who adds they were probably designed to match the speed of a trireme.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] It is probable that horse transports were galleys with a shallow draft, that allowed horses get off in the waters and embark via a ramp.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenids are known to have used vessels for connecting the banks of rivers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The bridges were built by joining vessels to one another and lashing them together, to erect a roadway with planks.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon reports such bridges, one made using 37 boats on Tigris, and another using seven on Maeander.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] During its early years under Cambyses, the Achaemenid navy is assumed to possess about 300 triremes, which was equal to the sum of the fleet of Egypt and its ally Polycrates of Samos.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] This number was later doubled, with 600 triremes mentioned in 494 and 490 BC.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The initial set-up of the navy (300 triremes) may have had up to 51,000 rowers and thousands of sailors and marines.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The original number of vessels in the fleet was eventually quadrupled, according to Greek sources.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Herodotus' account of naval forces under Xerxes I, put the number of warships in service at 1,207, in addition to 3,000 transport ships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Contemporary academic estimates range from 500 to 1,000 vessels, according to Matt Waters.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Scholars maintain that this number included large numbers of reserve ships, and the navy had not enough full oar crews to operate them all.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Herodotus also states that Persians arrived for the Battle of Marathon (490 BC) with 600 triremes and some horse transport vessels.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Though the number is rejected by some academics, Anthony J.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Papalas states that evidence does support this report.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Considering that each ship had an average of 50 oarsmen (the absolute minimum for a trireme) and 10 to 20 seamen and marines were also aboard, the navy compromised 36,000 to 42,000 men, at least.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] After the Battle of Salamis (480 BC), the fleet began to decline and never regained its peak numbers.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The largest figure estimated after 404 BC is 400 triremes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The number was still equal to, if not more than, the fleets of the Athenian alliance.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Xenophon wrote in *Anabasis*, "his (Cyrus the Younger) ensign was a golden eagle with outspread wings mounted upon a long shaft and this continues even unto this day as the ensign of the Persian king".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] While there is not much to confirm this, some scholars maintain that *Alexander Mosaic* contained a depiction of the standard (on the part which is now damaged), head of a bird in yellow on a red cloth.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] There is also a square plaque found at Apadana in plain, and it is quite possible that it shows the eagle.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The Achaemenid navy was the first true "imperial navy" that appeared in history.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] Persians are also credited for establishing the 'trireme navy' as the naval standard of their time.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The establishment of the Achaemenid navy set the basis of Iranian naval engineering, as well as "a powerful Persian maritime tradition that remained in the region until the arrival of the British East India Company and the Royal Navy by the mid-19th century AD".
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The naval forces affected the coastal subjects of the Achaemenid Empire to a great extent.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] They were put under much tighter control from the capital, and were heavily involved in military campaigns of the Achaemenids.
[src:maritime-silk-road/achaemenid-navy] The Sidonians profited financially from the naval base stationed in their city.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] Actium belonged originally to the Corinthian colonists of Anactorium, who probably founded the sanctuary of Apollo Actius.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] In the 3rd century BC it fell to the Acarnanians, who subsequently held their religious summits there.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] There was also an ancient festival named Actia, celebrated here in honour of the god.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] Augustus after his victory enlarged the temple, and revived the ancient festival, which was henceforth celebrated once in five years (πενταετηρίς, ludi quinquennales), with musical and gymnastic contests, and horse races.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] We learn from a Greek inscription found on the site of Actium, and which is probably prior to the time of Augustus, that the chief priest of the temple was called Ἱεραπόλος, and that his name was employed in official documents, like that of the first Archon at Athens, to mark the date.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] Strabo says that the temple was situated on an eminence, and that below was a plain with a grove of trees, and a dock-yard; and in another passage he describes the harbour as situated outside of the gulf.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] On the opposite coast of Epirus, Augustus founded the city of Nicopolis in honour of his victory.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] After the foundation of Nicopolis, a few buildings sprang up around the temple, and it served as a kind of suburb to Nicopolis.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] On October 8, 1980, the Greek Ministry of Transport and Communications reported that shipwrecks from the Battle of Actium had been located at Actium near the entrance to the Ambracan Gulf.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] In Summer 2009, archaeologists discovered the ruins of the Temple of Apollo and found two statue heads, one of Apollo, one of Artemis (Diana).
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] The peninsula is connected via an underwater tunnel to the city of Preveza in Epirus, on the opposite side of the mouth of the Ambracian Gulf.
[src:maritime-silk-road/actium] The total length of the tunnel is 1,570 metres (5,150 ft), of which 909 metres (2,982 ft) are located underwater.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The **Maritime Silk Road** or **Maritime Silk Route** is the maritime section of the historic Silk Road that connected Southeast Asia, East Asia, the Indian subcontinent, the Arabian Peninsula, eastern Africa, and Europe.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It began by the 2nd century BCE and flourished until the 15th century CE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Maritime Silk Road was primarily established and operated by Austronesian sailors in Southeast Asia who sailed large long-distance ocean-going sewn-plank and lashed-lug trade ships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The route was also utilized by the dhows of the Persian and Arab traders in the Arabian Sea and beyond, and the Tamil merchants in South Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] China also started building their own trade ships (*chuán*) and followed the routes in the later period, from the 10th to the 15th centuries CE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The term "Maritime Silk Road" is a modern name, acquired from its similarity to the overland Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The ancient maritime routes through the Indo-West Pacific (Southeast Asia and the Indian Ocean) had no particular name for the majority of its very long history.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Despite the modern name, the Maritime Silk Road involved exchanges in a wide variety of goods over a very wide region, not just silk or Asian exports.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Maritime Silk Road developed from the earlier Neolithic lingling-o jade maritime trade networks established by Austronesians in Southeast Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] This extensive ancient maritime trade network in Southeast Asia, covering a 3000-kilometer area around the South China Sea, existed long before the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It lasted for around 3,000 years, partially overlapping with the Maritime Silk Road, from 2000 BCE to 1000 CE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It was initially established by the indigenous peoples of Taiwan and the northern Philippines.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Raw nephrite jade (Fengtian jade) was sourced from deposits in eastern Taiwan and worked into ornaments and tools in the Philippines (the most notable and most numerous of are double-headed pendants and penannular earrings known as lingling-o).
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Taiwan-sourced jade declined in use after around 500 BCE, and non-Taiwanese jade and other materials became more common.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The distribution of these jade artifacts were also accompanied by other evidence of maritime trade and shared material culture particularly between the Austronesians of the Neolithic Philippines, southern Vietnam, and Borneo.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The wide distribution throughout Island Southeast Asia of the ceremonial bronze drums (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 600 BCE to 400 CE) sourced from the Dong Son culture of northern Vietnam is also evidence of the antiquity and density of this prehistoric Southeast Asian maritime network.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] During the operation of the maritime trade in jade artifacts, the Austronesian spice trade networks were also established by Islander Southeast Asians with Sri Lanka and Southern India by around 1500 to 600 BCE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] These early contacts resulted in the introduction of Austronesian crops and material culture to South Asia, including betel nut chewing, coconuts, sandalwood, domesticated bananas, sugarcane, cloves, and nutmeg.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It also introduced Austronesian sailing technologies like outrigger boats which are still utilized in Sri Lanka and southern India.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Semi-precious stone and glass ornaments showing northern Indian designs have also been recovered from the Khao Sam Kaeo (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 24 BCE to 276 CE) archaeological sites in Thailand, along with trade goods from the Austronesian Sa Huynh-Kalanay Interaction Sphere.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Both sites are coastal settlements and part of the jade trade network, indicating that the maritime routes of Austronesians had already reached South Asia by this period.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] South Asian crops like the mung bean and horsegram were also present in Khao Sam Kaeo, indicating the exchange was reciprocal.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] There is also indirect evidence of very early Austronesian contacts with Africa, based on the presence and spread of Austronesian domesticates like bananas, taro, chickens, and purple yam in Africa in the first millennium BCE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The western circuit of the Maritime Silk Road also developed from earlier maritime trade routes in West Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] These linked Sri Lanka, the Malabar Coast of India, Persia, Mesopotamia, Arabia, Egypt, the Horn of Africa, and the Greco-Roman civilizations in the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] These trade routes (initially only near-coastal, short-range, and small-scale) has existed since the Neolithic, from at least the Ubaid period (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] They became regular trade routes between urban centers in West Asia by the first millennium BCE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] By around the 2nd century BCE, the prehistoric Austronesian jade and spice trade networks in Southeast Asia fully connected with the maritime trade routes of South Asia, the Middle East, eastern Africa, and the Mediterranean, becoming what is now known as the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Prior to the 10th century, the eastern part of the route was primarily used by Southeast Asian Austronesian traders using distinctive sewn-plank and lashed-lug ships, although Persian and Tamil traders also sailed the western parts of the routes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It allowed the exchange of goods from East and Southeast Asia on one end, all the way to Europe and eastern Africa on the other.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Chinese records misidentified these kingdoms as being "Indian" due to the Indianization of these regions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Secondary routes also passed through the coastlines of the Gulf of Thailand; as well as through the Java Sea, Celebes Sea, Banda Sea, and the Sulu Sea, reconnecting with the main route through the northern Philippines and Taiwan.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The secondary routes also continue onward to the East China Sea and the Yellow Sea for a limited extent.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Glass artifacts from India and Egypt that passed through glassworkers in Southeast Asian and South Asian ports have been recovered from graves in the Korean peninsula (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 2nd-6th centuries CE), showing the furthest northeastern extent of the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The main route of the western regions of the Maritime Silk Road directly crosses the Indian Ocean from the northern tip of Sumatra (or through the Sunda Strait) to Sri Lanka, southern India and Bangladesh, and the Maldives.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It branches from here into routes through the Arabian Sea entering the Gulf of Oman (into the Persian Gulf), and the Gulf of Aden (into the Red Sea).
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Secondary routes also pass through the coastlines of the Bay of Bengal, the Arabian Sea, and southwards along the coast of East Africa to Zanzibar, the Comoros, Madagascar, and the Seychelles.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Maldives was of particular importance as a major hub for Austronesian sailors venturing through the western routes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The route was influential in the early spread of Hinduism and Buddhism to the east.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The close links of these religions to trade with South Asia led to the widespread adoption of Sanskrit as the trade lingua franca in the early Maritime Silk Road by the 4th century CE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Han and Tang dynasty Chinese records also indicate that the early Chinese Buddhist pilgrims to South Asia booked passage with the Austronesian ships (which they called the *k'un-lun po*) that traded in the Chinese port city of Guangzhou.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Books written by Chinese monks like Wan Chen and Hui-Lin contain detailed accounts of the large trading vessels from Southeast Asia dating back to at least the 3rd century CE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Austronesians were already sailing as far as East Africa and the Arabian Peninsula even during the earlier period.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Austronesians colonized the island of Madagascar off the coast of Africa some time in between the 1st century CE to the 6th or 7th centuries CE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It remained a part of the Maritime Silk Road, along with the nearby African, Arab, and Persian trading ports of Kilwa Kisiwani and Zanzibar (Tanzania), and other ports along the mainland coasts of modern Somalia, Kenya, and Mozambique.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Records from Portuguese explorers in the late 15th and early 16th centuries indicate that direct maritime links between Indonesia and Madagascar persisted up until shortly before the colonial period.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It emerged through the conquest and subjugation of neighboring thalassocracies.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] These included Melayu, Kedah, Tarumanagara, and Mataram, among others.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] These polities controlled the sea lanes in Southeast Asia and exploited the spice trade of the Spice Islands, as well as maritime trade-routes between India and China.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] By the 7th century CE, Arab dhow traders also ventured into the routes earlier pioneered by Persian traders to Sri Lanka, coinciding with the spread of Islam throughout West Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] They pushed deeper east into Srivijaya and Guangzhou, leading to the earliest spread of Islam into Southeast Asian polities.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] During this period, the Persian language (*Fārsī*), became the dominant lingua franca of both the Maritime and overland Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] By the 10th to 13th centuries, there was an economic boom in maritime trade, led primarily by the fact that the Song dynasty of China started building its own trading ships (*chuán*) capable of sailing sea routes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Song court also loosened restrictions on private trade, despite the traditional Chinese Confucian disdain for trade.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] This was partly due to the loss of access by the Song dynasty to the overland Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Song maritime technology was developed from observing Southeast Asian Austronesian ships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Before this, Chinese ships were essentially fluvial (riverine) in nature and operation and were not seaworthy.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Song started sending trading expeditions to the region they referred to as *Nan hai* (Chinese: 南海; pinyin: *Nánhǎi*; lit.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 'South Seas'), mostly still dominated by Srivijaya, venturing as far south as the Sulu Sea and the Java Sea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] This led to the establishment of new trading ports in Southeast Asia (like in Java and Sumatra) that specifically catered to the Chinese demand for goods like "dragon's brain perfume" (camphor) and other exotica.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Quanzhou also became a major Chinese trading port during this period, joining the older trading port of Guangzhou.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Both became tightly linked to their Southeast Asian counterparts, leading historians to characterize the distinct trading circuit in this region as the "Asian Mediterranean", from its similarity to the Mediterranean Sea Trade.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] However, the Song enacted a 9-month limit on how long trade ships can stay at sea, limiting the range of Chinese trade ships to Southeast Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Arab and Tamil traders also increased their participation with direct trade to Chinese ports through the Strait of Malacca in the 10th to 13th centuries.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The surprise naval expeditions in 1025 of Rajendra I of the Tamil Chola Empire against Srivijaya's ports along the strait, may have been motivated by Srivijaya's attempt to regulate or block Tamil trading guilds.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Chola invasions ended Srivijaya's monopoly on the Strait of Malacca routes for around a century, during which many of the Srivijayan cities were occupied by the Chola.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Srivijaya was left greatly weakened and was eventually subjugated by Singhasari by around 1275, before finally being absorbed by the successor thalassocracy of Majapahit (1293–1527).
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] China was invaded by the Mongol Yuan dynasty in the 13th century.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Chinese shipping during this period was monopolized by the state, via foreign Muslim merchants partnered with the Yuan government in *ortogh* relationships.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Though unlike the Song, the Yuan lifted the 9-month limit, allowing Chinese trade to venture as far as South Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Yuan also attempted naval invasions on Japan, Majapahit, and Vietnam (Austronesian Champa, and Kinh Đại Việt).
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] China itself was later devastated by floods, drought, and famine.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Concurrently, the Black Death was sweeping through Europe and Western Asia.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] All of these factors led to a slump in trade along the Maritime Silk Road in the 14th century.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] In the late 14th century, the city-state of Palembang (the former capital of Srivijaya, which has since Islamized) sent an envoy to the Hongwu Emperor, the first emperor of the Ming dynasty (which overthrew the Yuan), to reestablish trade routes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The ruler of Palembang was hoping to regain the city's former wealth, independent of the Hindu-Buddhist Majapahit.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Hayam Wuruk of Majapahit, angry at the actions of the vassal state, sent a punitive naval attack on Palembang in 1377, causing a diaspora of princes and nobles to the Kingdom of Singapura.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Singapura, in turn, was attacked and sacked in 1398.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Parameswara, originally from Palembang and the last ruler of Singapura, fled to the western coast of the Malay Peninsula and founded the Muslim Sultanate of Malacca in the early 15th century.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] During the same period in the early 15th century, the Ming dynasty launched the expeditions of Zheng He, with the goal of forcing the "barbarian kings" of Southeast Asia to resume sending "tribute" (i.e. regular trade routes) to the Ming court.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] This was typical of the Sinocentric views at the time of viewing "trade as tribute".
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Zheng He's expeditions were short-lived, as the drain in imperial funds and the threat of invasion from the north led the Xuande Emperor to cease the expeditions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] He enacted the *hai jin* laws shortly after, and banned outgoing trade altogether.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Although ultimately, Zheng He's expeditions were successful in their goal of restoring trade relations with Southeast Asia (in this case, Malacca) and the Ming dynasty.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] By the mid-15th century, the Sultanate of Malacca had gained effective control of the Strait of Malacca.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Further weakening Majapahit's influence greatly, which was already suffering from internal rebellions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Trade from Malacca continued to arrive in Chinese ports in the brief period prior to the fall of Majapahit, the Portuguese invasion of Malacca, and the fall of the Ming dynasty to the Manchu invasions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Maritime Silk Route was disrupted by the colonial era in the 16th century, essentially being replaced with European trade routes.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Shipbuilding of the formerly dominant Southeast Asian trading ships (*jong*, the source of the English term "junk") declined until it ceased entirely by the 17th century.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Although Chinese-built *chuán* survived until modern times.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] There was new demand for spices from Southeast Asia and textiles from India and China, but these were now linked with direct trade routes to the European market, instead of passing through regional ports.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] By the 16th century, the Age of Exploration had begun.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Portuguese Empire's capture of Malacca led to the transfer of the trade centers to the sultanates of Aceh and Johor.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Spanish Empire in the Philippines established the Manila-Acapulco Galleon Trade, which acquired trade goods like Chinaware and silk from Quanzhou and Zhangzhou, and spices (mostly from the Spice Islands of Moluccas) for the markets in Latin America and Europe.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] All of which were traded over the Pacific to Acapulco in Mexico and throughout the Spanish Americas; and also later traded via the *Flota de Indias* (Spanish treasure fleet) from Veracruz in Mexico to Seville in Spain and onward throughout Europe.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Manila-Acapulco Galleon Trade route was the first permanent trade route across the Pacific.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Similarly, the West Indies Spanish treasure fleet was the first permanent transatlantic trade route in history.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Both bypassed the Indian Ocean Maritime Silk Road entirely.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The archaeological evidence of the Maritime Silk Road include numerous shipwrecks recovered along the route carrying (or associated with) trade goods sourced from various far-flung ports.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The origins of these early ships are readily identifiable by a combination of distinctive features and shipbuilding techniques used (such as lashed-lug and sewn boat traditions).
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 660-780 CE), the Butuan ship burials (multiple boats ranging from c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 689 to 988 CE), the Chau Tan shipwreck (c. late 8th to early 9th century CE), the Intan wreck (c. early to mid-10th century CE), the Karawang shipwreck (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 10th century CE), and the Cirebon wreck (c. late 10th century CE), among others.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Almost all of the ships recovered from Southeast Asia before the 10th century belong to the Austronesian shipbuilding traditions, displaying variations and combinations of sewn-plank and lashed-lug techniques.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Another early partial shipwreck, the Pak Klong Kluay shipwreck (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 2nd century CE), uniquely joined planks using pegged mortise and tenon joints.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Though this is similar to Phoenician and later Greco-Roman shipbuilding techniques, the ship is also Austronesian, with timber sourced locally from Southeast Asian trees and evidence of lashed-lug techniques on the inner surface.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Some authors have pointed to this as evidence that the Phoenician mortise and tenon shipbuilding techniques originally developed outside of the Mediterranean.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Only two shipwrecks recovered from Southeast Asia prior to the 10th century CE are not Austronesian and exhibit early Arab dhow shipbuilding techniques: the Phanom-Surin ship (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 7th century CE) and the Belitung shipwreck (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 826 CE), Dhows similarly use sewn-plank techniques, but differ from Austronesian sewn-plank techniques in which the stitches are only visible from the inner surfaces and are discontinuous.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] They also did not originally use lashed-lug techniques, though later ships like the Belitung shipwreck adopted it from contact with Austronesian shipbuilders.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Some of the timber used on the major components of the Phanom-Surin ship is also sourced from Southeast Asian trees, despite its West Asian construction.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Similarly, some of the later Austronesian ships display elements of West Asian shipbuilding techniques (like cross-armed anchors) suggesting that the merchants and crew of the ships had multinational origins, regardless of where the ships were originally built.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] China did not start building sea-going ships that ventured into the Maritime Silk Road until the Song dynasty (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The earliest known Chinese shipwrecks found along the Maritime Silk Road are the Ming-era Turiang wreck (c.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 1305-1370 CE) and the Bakau wreck (c. early 15th century CE).
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Chinese-built ships (*chuán*) are also readily identifiable by being built with iron nails and clamps, in contrast to Austronesian and Western Asian ships which were built entirely with wood joining and fiber lashings.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Other distinctive features of Chinese ships which developed from their earlier fluvial (riverine) ship technologies include a flat-bottomed design (the keel was absent), a central rudder (instead of two side-mounted quarter rudders), and the division of the hull into water-tight compartments.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] By around the end of the Maritime Silk Road in the 14th and 15th century, ships that combined features of both Chinese and Austronesian boatbuilding traditions also start to appear, even reaching as far as India.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Indian ships are similarly absent in the archaeological context in the eastern routes of the Maritime Silk Road prior to the 10th century CE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] 2nd century CE) is the earliest evidence of maritime networking in the Indian Ocean, but it only involved local exchanges in raw materials along the South Indian coast.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The archaeological evidence demonstrates that the trading ships in the South China Sea and the Indian Ocean were Austronesian sewn-plank and lashed-lug vessels and Arab dhows prior to the 10th century CE.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Austronesian vessels dominated the long-distance maritime trade for much of the history of the Maritime Silk Road.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Chinese ceramics are also valuable archaeological markers of the Maritime Silk Road due to their relative indestructibility and the fact that they can be precisely dated.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] They first entered Southeast Asia via the ancient Austronesian maritime networks in the 2nd century BCE but were not initially a major export of China.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] They became exported by the Tang dynasty (618-907 CE), rapidly increased in volume during the Song (960-1279 CE) and Yuan dynasties (1279-1367 CE), before declining in the Ming Dynasty (1368-1643 CE), and ceasing entirely in the 15th century.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Their distribution throughout the Southeast Asian trade network is uneven, reflecting differences in local demand, buying power, and trade specialization.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The largest concentrations of Chinese ceramics are found along the Strait of Melaka and Java, with other significant concentrations in Sulawesi, Borneo, the Riau Archipelago, and the Philippines.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Although usually spoken of in modern times in the context of the Eurocentric and Sinocentric demand for luxury goods and exotica by the Roman and Chinese empires (hence the fixation on silk in its name), the goods carried by the trading ships varied by which product was in demand by region and port.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] They included ceramics, glass, beads, gems, ivory, fragrant wood, metals (both raw and finished goods), textiles (including silk), food (including grain, wine, and spices), aromatics, and animals, among others.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Ivory, in particular, was a significant export of east Africa (originating from overland trade routes through the African interior), leading Chirikure (2022) to label the western leg of the trade route as the "**Maritime Ivory Route**".
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It was also not small-scale trade or high value-low volume trade as some earlier historians had assumed.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The goods carried by recovered shipwrecks show that they engaged in merchant capitalism.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] A very large number of goods, often mass-produced, were traded along the route.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The trade route encompassed numbers of seas and ocean; including South China Sea, Strait of Malacca, Indian Ocean, Gulf of Bengal, Arabian Sea, Persian Gulf and the Red Sea.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The maritime route overlaps with historic Southeast Asian maritime trade, spice trade, Indian Ocean trade and after 8th century—the Arabian naval trade network.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The network also extend eastward to the East China Sea and the Yellow Sea to connect China with the Korean Peninsula and the Japanese archipelago.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The Maritime Silk Road differed significantly in several aspects from the overland Silk Road, from where it acquired its name, and thus should not be viewed as a mere extension of it.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Traders traveling through the Maritime Silk Road could span the entire distance of the maritime routes, instead of through regional relays as with the overland route.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Ships could carry far larger amounts of goods, creating greater economic impact with each exchange.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Goods carried by the ships also differed from goods carried by caravans.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Traders on the maritime route faced different perils like weather and piracy, but they were not affected by political instability and could simply avoid areas in conflict.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] In May 2017, experts from various fields held a meeting in London to discuss the proposal to nominate "Maritime Silk Route" as a new UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The academic research on the ancient Maritime Silk Road has been appropriated and mythologized by modern countries for political reasons.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] China, in particular, uses a mythologized image of the Maritime Silk Road for its Belt and Road Initiative, first proposed by General Secretary of the Chinese Communist Party Xi Jinping during a visit to Indonesia in 2015.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] It attempts to reconnect the old trade routes between the port cities of Southeast Asia and the Indian Ocean, and assumes erroneously that Chinese sailors played a major role in developing the route.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] India has also mythologized the Maritime Silk Road with Project Mausam, launched in 2014, which similarly attempts to reconnect old trade links with surrounding countries in the Indian Ocean.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] India also portrays itself as playing a central role in the Maritime Silk Road, and early Indian nationalist historians like R.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Majumdar often depicted its trade connections and the overwhelmingly one way cultural diffusion ("overwhelmingly one way" according to leading historian William Dalrymple, and the overall process is generally accepted as "Indianisation.") as "Indian colonization" under the vision of a Greater India.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The old theories about "colonization" has been replaced by an understanding of complexities in South and South-east Asian interactions.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] The process occurred through the movement of priests, artisans, merchants, and scholars, along with the initiatives of local people.
[src:maritime-silk-road/maritime-silk-road] Even though the cross-cultural exchange might be asymmetrical, historians have tried to identify the westward movement of ideas from South-east Asia to India through the route, such as musical instruments, ceramic and ship building techniques.
